      "content": "Yes, it is absolutely weird because the sensation feels so visceral, but it is indeed happening right inside the muscle fibers themselves, specifically within the sarcoplasm (the fluid part of the cell). The hydrogen ions (the \"acid\" part) flood into the sarcoplasm and interfere with calcium ions, which are the tiny keys that unlock the actin and myosin filaments to pull you forward. Without those keys working properly, the muscle fibers can't contract efficiently, and the nerves inside the fiber get overwhelmed by the low pH, sending that \"burning\" signal up your spinal cord to your brain.\n\nYou can think of it like a construction site where the workers (muscle fibers) are trying to lift heavy beams (contract), but the foreman (calcium) is confused because the safety guards (hydrogen ions) are blocking his instructions. The \"physical\" feeling is your brain reacting to the confused workers and the chaotic environment inside the cell. Once you cool down, the cleanup crew (blood flow and the Cori cycle) sweeps the ions away, the foreman gets his keys back, and the construction resumes smoothly.\n\nIt's a bit like a tiny, high-stress meeting in a small room where",
